  <p>Many pregnant women experience pelvic or lumbar pain during their pregnancy. These pains reflect the transformations the body is going through: hormones, posture, centre of gravity. Osteopathy can support you through this period more comfortably and serenely.</p>

  <h2>Why does the body hurt during pregnancy?</h2>
  <p>Pregnancy brings significant changes: gradual weight gain, a shifting centre of gravity, ligament relaxation under the effect of relaxin, and the growing uterus displacing surrounding organs. These adaptations can create tension in the spine, pelvis and diaphragm.</p>
  <p>The most common pains are:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Lower back pain:</strong> worsening at the end of the day or after prolonged standing</li>
    <li><strong>Pelvic pain:</strong> in the pubis, sacrum or coccyx</li>
    <li><strong>Pubic symphysis pain (SPD):</strong> affecting around 20% of pregnant women</li>
    <li><strong>Pregnancy-related sciatica:</strong> due to compression of the nerve by the uterus or muscle tension</li>
    <li><strong>Difficulty sleeping</strong> linked to tension in the back and hips</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Is it safe during pregnancy?</h2>
  <p>Yes. An osteopath who treats pregnant women adapts their approach entirely to this situation. The techniques used are gentle, with no pressure on the abdomen, and designed to respect the comfort of both mother and baby at every stage of pregnancy.</p>

  <div class="highlight">
    Always inform your osteopath of your pregnancy at the time of booking. Certain contraindications exist in cases of high-risk pregnancy, threatened premature labour or placenta praevia. Your gynaecological follow-up remains the priority.
  </div>

  <h2>When should you consult?</h2>
  <p>As soon as you feel pain or tension, it is the right time to consult. Cécile Arnoux adapts her care to your stage of pregnancy and personal situation. Do not hesitate to mention this when booking your appointment.</p>

  <h2>Osteopathy after childbirth</h2>
  <p>Childbirth places intense strain on the pelvis, perineum and spine. After the birth, a consultation can help to:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Rebalance the pelvis and sacrum</li>
    <li>Relieve back pain related to breastfeeding and carrying</li>
    <li>Support recovery after an episiotomy or caesarean section</li>
  </ul>
  <p>This approach complements pelvic floor rehabilitation; the two do not replace each other.</p>
